title: France in the Nineteenth Century
creator: Elizabeth Wormeley Latimer
source: Librivox recording of a public-domain text
description: LibriVox recording of France in the Nineteenth Century, by Elizabeth Wormeley Latimer. Read by Cathy Barratt. Author Elizabeth Latimer synthesizes notes from a variety of sources to produce this summary of the nation of France in the 19th century. (Summary by Cathy Barratt) For further information, including links to online text, reader information, RSS feeds, CD cover or other formats (if available), please go to the LibriVox catalog page for this recording. For more free audio books or to become a volunteer reader, visit LibriVox.org. Download M4B 01-18 (202MB) Download M4B 19-35 (185MB)
subject: librivox; audiobook; history

reviews.reviewbody: If the two chapters on the Paris Commune seems written by a pollyanna and dubious on her sources and biased writing.  Just read Wikipedia's page on the Paris Commune, or most sources.  It is totally different.  If anything the communards were the moderate and nasty Adolphe Thiers and expoitative  were much more bloodthirsty than the communards.  The communards should have went all the way to Versailles at the beginning to arrest Thiers and company.  The brutal crushing of the the Paris Commune of 1871 is one of history's great tragedies.  This is one of most right wing biased "history" of the Paris Commune.   If these chapters are representative of the whole audio book, don't waste your time.
reviews.reviewtitle: Paris Commune chapters are reactionary, misleading
